{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte does not identify a single specific Roman *institution* (such as the Senate, census, or collegia) as degraded by slavery in *Traité de Législation*, Vol. IV, Chapter 5.**[^1]\n\nInstead, he argues that slavery degraded **all useful labors and industrial occupations** (\"tous les travaux utiles\" and related professions) in the eyes of the free population.[^2][^3] Among Romans, this contempt drove free cultivators from the countryside (replaced by slave-worked pastures), then barred non-aristocratic free persons from arts and commerce (taken over by aristocratic-owned slaves). Free non-owners could no longer publicly trade or practice crafts without shame, swelling the proletarian class dependent on public aid, pillage, or clandestine work.[^4][^5]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [Chapter 5](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/05-de-l-influence-de-l-esclavage-sur-l-existence-des-/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [p-e1fd8b](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/05-de-l-influence-de-l-esclavage-sur-l-existence-des-/translation/#p-e1fd8b).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [p-89442a](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/05-de-l-influence-de-l-esclavage-sur-l-existence-des-/translation/#p-89442a).\n\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [p-ef4dc3](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/05-de-l-influence-de-l-esclavage-sur-l-existence-des-/translation/#p-ef4dc3).\n\n[^5]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [p-1cfc42](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/05-de-l-influence-de-l-esclavage-sur-l-existence-des-/translation/#p-1cfc42).",
